{"parse":{"title":"mountain","pageid":8412,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Mountain}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[File:Winter sun on Norwegian mountain.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A snow-covered '''mountain''' (sense 1).]]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*men-|id=stand out}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|mountayne}}, {{m|enm|mountain}}, {{m|enm|montaigne}}, from {{der|en|xno|montaigne|muntaine}}, {{m|fro|montaigne|muntaigne}}, from {{der|en|la-eme|montānia}}, a collective based on {{der|en|la|mōns|montem|t=mountain}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*monti}} (compare {{cog|cy|mynydd||mountain}}, {{cog|sq|mat||bank, shore}}, {{cog|ae|𐬨𐬀𐬙𐬌|t=promontory}}), from {{m|ine-pro|*men-||to project, stick out}}. Displaced native {{ncog|en|barrow}} (from {{ncog|ang|beorg}}) and {{m|en|down}} (from {{ncog|ang|dūn}}), and partially displaced non-native {{cog|ang|munt}}, from Latin {{m|la|mōns}} (whence {{cog|en|mount}}).\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|UK}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈmaʊn.tɪn/|a=RP}}\n*** {{audio|en|En-uk-mountain.ogg|a=UK}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈmuːn.tɪn/|a=Northumbrian}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈmaʊn.t(ə)n/|[ˈmaʊn.tn̩]|a=GA}}<ref>{{R:Dictionary.com}},</ref><ref>{{cite-web |title=OALD |titleurl=http://oald8.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/dictionary/mountain |accessdate=26 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101214955/http://oald8.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/dictionary/mountain |archivedate=1 November 2012 }}</ref> {{IPAchar|[ˈmãʊ̯̃(n)ʔn̩]|[ˈmæ̃ʊ̯̃(n)ʔn̩]}}\n* {{audio|en|En-us-mountain.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Exilexi-mountain.wav}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈmaʊn.tən/|a=IE}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈmæʊn.tən/|/ˈmɛʊn.tən/|a=Dublin}}\n* {{IPA|en|/maʊn.te(ɪ)n/|a=Indic}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊntɪn|q1=Received Pronunciation|aʊntən|q2=General American|s=2}}\n* {{hyphenation|en|caption=US|moun|tain}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q8502}} {{lb|en|countable}} An [[elevation]] of land of considerable dimensions rising more or less [[abruptly]], forming a [[conspicuous]] figure in the landscape, usually having a small extent of surface at its [[summit]]. {{defdate|from 12th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|[[Everest]] is the highest '''mountain''' in the world.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We spent the weekend hiking in the '''mountains'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We collected plant specimens from '''mountain''' meadows above 2000 meters.<!--This ux shows attributive use.-->}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Jeremiah|50|6||My people hath been lost sheep: their shepherds have caused them to go astray, they have turned them away ''on'' the '''mountains''': they have gone from '''mountain''' to hill, they have forgotten their restingplace.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1807|location=London|publisher=Nicol, White, Faulders & Asperne|author=Joseph Wilson|chapter=Preliminary Observations|title=A History of Mountains, Geographical and Mineralogical|volume=1|pages=xlvi–xlvii|pageurl=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/chi.102238731?urlappend=%3Bseq=54|text=Wherever a geologist directs his attention in the midst of a scene of '''mountains''', traces of ruin and decay always meet his eye; and the lofty prominences of our globe, supposed to be the most permanent of nature's works, every where display unequivocal marks of the lapse and effects of time.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1829|author=w:Edgar Allan Poe|chapter={{w|Tamerlane (poem)|Tamerlane}}|title=Al Aaraaf, Tamerlane and Minor Poems|passage=We walk’d together on the crown<br>Of a high '''mountain''' which look’d down<br>Afar from its proud natural towers<br>Of rock and forest, on the hills— […]}}\n# {{lb|en|countable}} Something very large in size or quantity; a huge [[amount]]; a great [[heap]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He was a real '''mountain''' of a man, standing seven feet tall.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There's still a '''mountain''' of work to do.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2002-12-09|title=A Mountain of Lies?|work=The Economist|url=https://www.economist.com/news/2002/12/09/a-mountain-of-lies|text=Iraq says the '''mountain''' of documentation it has provided to the United Nations shows it is innocent of harbouring weapons of mass destruction. America continues to maintain that it has evidence that this is a pack of lies.}}\n# {{lb|en|figuratively}} A difficult [[task]] or challenge.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2011-10-01|author=Phil Dawkes|title=Sunderland 2 - 2 West Brom|work=BBC Sport|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/15045630.stm|passage=Five minutes into the game the Black Cats were facing a '''mountain''', partly because of West Brom's newly-found ruthlessness in front of goal but also as a result of the home side's defensive generosity.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|now|historical}} [[wine|Wine]] from [[Malaga]] made from [[grape]]s that grow on a mountain. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1785-1789|author=w:James Boswell|title=The English Experiment (diaries)|passage=Called on Courtenay, with whom I walked to Hampstead Heath, and got into excellent spirits, enjoying fine fresh air; then dined with him tête-a-tête on mutton broth and mackerel and drank '''mountain''' and old port moderately.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|slang}} A [[woman]]'s large [[breast]].\n# {{lb|en|cartomancy}} The twenty-first [[Lenormand]] card.\n\n====Usage notes====\n* As with the names of {{l|en|river|rivers}} and {{l|en|lake|lakes}}, the names of mountains are typically formed by adding the generic word before or after the unique term. In the case of mountains, when the word precedes the unique term, {{m|en|mount}} is used: {{m|en|Mount Olympus}}, {{m|en|Mount Everest}}, {{m|en|Mount Tai}}; when the word follows the unique term, ''mountain'' is used: {{m|en|Crowfoot Mountain}}, {{m|en|Blue Mountain}}, {{m|en|Rugged Mountain}}. Generally speaking, such names will be adjectives or attributive nouns, but many foreign placenames formed with adjectives—as China's {{m|en|Huashan}}—are translated as though they were proper names: {{m|en|Mount Hua}} instead of ''Hua Mountain'' or ''Flourishing Mountain''. [[mountain chain|Mountain chains]] are never named with {{m|en|mount}}, only with {{m|en|mountains}}, a translated term, or a pluralized name.\n\n====Synonyms====\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Terms derived from Germanic roots\n|barrow<q:obsolete in some senses>\n|berg<q:chiefly South Africa>\n|berry<q:chiefly dialectal>\n|pike<q:chiefly Northern England>\n}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Of the sense “an elevation of land”\n|Aspen Mountain|Rocky Mountain\n|Battle Mountain\n|Black Mountains|Big Mountain\n|Castle Mountain\n|folded mountain\n|Iron Mountain\n|Pine Mountain\n|table mountain,Table Mountain,Table Mountains\n|volcano\n}}\n\n====Meronyms====\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Of the sense “an elevation of land”\n|mountainside\n|mountainslope\n|mountaintop\n|peak\n}}\n\n====Holonyms====\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Of the sense “an elevation of land”\n|Blue Mountains\n|mountain chain\n|mountain range\n|Qin Mountains\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Single-word terms derived from “mountain”\n|intermountain<pos:adjective>\n|mountaineer<pos:noun/verb>| mountain devil\n||mountaineering<pos:noun>\n|nonmountaineer<pos:noun>\n|mountainless<pos:adjective>\n|mountainscape<pos:noun>\n|mountainwards<pos:adverb>\n|mountainy<pos:adjective>\n|Mountain<pos:proper noun>|intramountain|midmountain|mountainboard|mountained|mountainer|mountainet|mountaingem|mountainlike|mountainness|mountainward|municycling|submountain|transmountain|undermountain|upmountain\n}}\n\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Attributive uses of the noun “mountain”\n|Berry Mountain\n|Black Mountain\n|Blue Mountain\n|Blue Mountain Heights\n|Blue Mountains\n|Bony Mountain\n|Bowen Mountain\n|Browns Mountain\n|Bunya Mountain\n|Camp Mountain\n|Captains Mountain\n|Chinese mountain cat|mountain motor|mountain string|mountain-elf\n|Clear Mountain\n|Cooroy Mountain\n|Cradle Mountain\n|Doctor George Mountain\n|Dorrigo Mountain\n|Gemini Mountains\n|Glass House Mountains\n|Gowrie Mountain\n|Kiels Mountain\n|Little Mountain\n|Mangrove Mountain\n|Mothar Mountain\n|Mountainair|mountain weasel|mountain cavy|Mountain Kingdom|Steeple Mountain\n|mountain apple|Andean mountain cat\n|mountain ash,Mountain Ash\n|Mountain Bay\n|mountain bearberry|mountain bilberry\n|mountain bike| mountain ghost|mountain holly\n|mountain boarding| mountain-elf|Mountain Lakes\n|mountain building|Mountain Daylight Time|Mountain Time\n|mountain buzzard|mountain knotgrass\n|Mountain Camp\n|mountain cat\n|Mountain City\n|mountain climbing\n|mountain cranberry\n|Mountain Creek\n|mountain dew\n|mountain dulcimer|mountain parsley\n|mountain fever|Mountain Standard Time Zone|Mountain Time Zone\n|mountain goat\n|mountain gorilla|Welsh mountain pony\n|mountain hare|mountain unicycle|mountain unicycling\n|Mountain Home\n|Mountain Lagoon\n|mountain laurel\n|mountain lion\n|mountain reindeer\n|Mountain River\n|mountain sheep|Riding Mountain West\n|mountain sickness\n|Mountain Standard Time\n|Mountain Street\n|Mountain Top\n|mountain top removal mining\n|mountain unit|mountain pine beetle|mountain pride\n|Mountain View\n|Mountain View County\n|mountain zebra\n|Mumbulla Mountain\n|Myrtle Mountain\n|Nullo Mountain\n|Pine Mountain\n|Pointer Mountain\n|Round Mountain\n|Saddleback Mountain\n|Scrubby Mountain\n|Spring Mountain\n|Stoliczka's mountain vole\n|Tamborine Mountain\n|Towen Mountain\n|White Cloud Mountain minnow\n|White Mountain\n|Wights Mountain\n}}\n\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Idioms with the word “mountain”\n|have a mountain to climb\n|make a mountain out of a molehill\n|snow on the mountain\n}}\n\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Proverbs with the word “mountain”\n|faith will move mountains\n|if the mountain won't come to Muhammad\n}}\n\n{{col4|en|title=Other terms containing the word \"mountain\" (unsorted)|acute mountain sickness\n|Bavarian mountain hound\n|Bernese mountain dog||mountain phlox|people mountain people sea\n|butter mountain\n|Canby's mountain lover\n|cat-a-mountain|Castle Mountain|Mountain Jew\n|cat o' mountain|fire mountain\n|fire-on-the-mountain\n|fold mountain|mountain boubou|mountain sooty boubou\n|Hartmann's mountain zebra\n|Illawarra mountain pine\n|Japanese mountain yam\n|king shit of fuck mountain\n|Larch Mountain|man-mountain\n|mountain antelope\n|mountain avens\n|mountain avocetbill\n|mountain beaver\n|mountain bicycle\n|mountain biker\n|mountain biking\n|mountain blue\n|mountain bluebird\n|mountain bramble\n|mountain cabbage\n|mountain carpet clover\n|mountain cheese\n|mountain chickadee\n|mountain chicken\n|mountain climber\n|mountain clouded yellow\n|mountain cork\n|mountain crystal\n|mountain deer\n|mountain degu\n|mountain fir clubmoss\n|mountain flax\n|mountain fold\n|mountain grape\n|mountain green\n|mountain guide\n|mountain gun\n|mountain hemlock\n|mountain howitzer\n|mountain in labour\n|mountain leader\n|mountain leather\n|mountain limestone\n|mountain lioness\n|mountain lover\n|mountain mahogany\n|mountain man\n|mountain maple\n|mountain marrow\n|mountain meal\n|mountain milk\n|mountain mint\n|mountain misery\n|mountain nyala\n|mountain oyster\n|mountain panther\n|mountain papaya\n|mountain parrot\n|mountain pass\n|mountain pawpaw\n|mountain pecker\n|mountain pine\n|mountain plum\n|mountain quail\n|mountain rat\n|mountain rescue\n|mountain rescuer\n|mountain rice\n|mountain ringlet\n|mountain shrike\n|mountain soap\n|mountain soursop\n|mountain specter\n|mountain spectre\n|mountain spinach\n|mountain tallow\n|mountain tea\n|mountain tobacco\n|mountain to climb\n|mountain top\n|mountain vole\n|mountain wagtail\n|mountain wolf\n|Savage Mountain\n|snow-on-the-mountain\n|snow on the mountain top\n|trans-mountain\n|White Mountain\n|White Mountains\n|mountain belt\n|mountain system\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col|en|n=4|title=Terms derived from Latin “{{m|la|mōns}}”\n|amount<pos:noun/verb>\n|dismount<pos:verb>\n|montane<pos:adjective/noun>\n|montanic<pos:adjective>\n|mount<pos:noun/verb>\n|demount<pos:verb>\n|unmount<pos:verb>\n|mountainous<pos:adjective>\n|intramountainous<pos:adjective>\n|mountainously<pos:adverb>\n|mountainousness<pos:noun>\n|nonmountainous<pos:adjective>\n|unmountainous<pos:adjective>\n|paramount<pos:adjective>\n|sermountain<pos:noun>\n|surmount<pos:verb>\n}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top-see|large mass of earth and rock|mount}}\n* Abaga: {{t|abg|àg̶ònáì}}\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|ашьха}}\n* Acehnese: {{t|ace|gunong}}\n* Afar: {{t|aa|qaléyta}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|berg}}\n* Ahom: {{t|aho|𑜁𑜧}}\n* Ainu: {{t|ain|イワ|tr=iwa}}, {{t|ain|キㇺ|tr=kim}}\n* Akkadian: {{t|akk|𒆳|m|tr=šadûm}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|mal|m}}, {{t+|sq|bjeshkë|f}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|туу}}\n* Alviri-Vidari: {{t|avd|کمر|tr=kamer}} {{qualifier|Vidari}}\n* Ama: {{t|amm|yu}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|ተራራ}}, {{t|am|ጋራ}}\n* Antillean Creole: {{t|gcf|montangn|f}}\n* Apache:\n*: Western Apache: {{t|apw|dził}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|جَبَل|m}}, {{t+|ar|طُور|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|جبل|m|tr=gabal}}\n*: Juba Arabic: {{t|pga|jebel}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|جبل|m|tr=jbal}}\n* Aragonese: {{t+|an|montaña|f}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܛܘܪܐ|m|tr=ṭūrā}}\n*: Classical Syriac: {{t|syc|ܛܘܪܐ|m|tr=ṭūrā}}\n*: Jewish Aramaic: {{t|arc|טוּרָא|m|tr=ṭūrā}}\n* Argobba: {{t|agj|ተራራ|tr=tärara}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|լեռ}}, {{t+|hy|սար}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|munti|m}}, {{t|rup|munte|m}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|পর্বত}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|monte|m}}\n* Atayal: {{t|tay|rgyax}}\n* Avar: {{t|av|мегӏер}}\n* Avestan: {{t|ae|𐬐𐬀𐬊𐬟𐬀}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|dağ}}\n* Baluchi: {{t|bal|کوہ|tr=koh}}\n* Banjarese: {{t|bjn|gunung}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|тау}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|mendi}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|гара́|f}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|পর্বত}}, {{t+|bn|পাহাড়}}\n* Bidayuh:\n*: Bau Bidayuh: {{t|sne|dorod}}, {{t|sne|bung}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol:\n*:: Bikol Legazpi: {{t+|bcl|bulod}}\n*:: Bikol Naga: {{t|bcl|bukid}}\n* Boloki: {{t|bkt|ngómbá}}\n* Bontoc:\n*: Eastern Bontoc: {{t|ebk|filig}}, {{t|ebk|chontog}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|menez|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|планина́|f}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my